    "main_findings": [
      {
        "dataset_used": "TIMSS 2019 Grade 8 Science (44 countries/regions)",
        "target_variable": "Science achievement (Plausible Values BSSSCI01–BSSSCI05)",
        "top_predictors": [
          "Socioeconomic background (SES)",
          "Feel confident about science",
          "Instructional time (teachers)",
          "Science experiment frequency",
          "Curriculum type (Integrated vs Separated)"
        ],
        "performance_metrics": "Random Forest — R² (testing) averaged across PVs: 0.51; RMSE (testing) averaged across PVs: 74.92. Propensity score matching — integrated group significantly higher than separated after controlling covariates (Mann–Whitney U with Bonferroni correction); effect sizes small (Cohen’s d ≈ 0.20–0.24 across PVs).",
        "standardized_conclusion": "Using TIMSS 2019 Grade 8 Science the study leveraged socioeconomic background, science confidence, instructional time, and science experiment frequency (with curriculum type as a key comparison variable) to predict science achievement using Random Forest, finding that Random Forest outperformed linear regression, lasso regression, decision trees, and neural networks and that curriculum type had only a weak direct predictive role while integrated curricula showed a small positive advantage after propensity score matching. This indicates that gression, lasso regression, decision trees, and neural networks and that curriculum type had only a weak direct predictive role while integrated curricula showed a small positive advantage after propensity score matching."
      }
    ],
    "outcome_summary": "The study analyzes TIMSS 2019 Grade 8 Science data from 44 countries/regions (N=309,511 after cleaning) to compare integrated vs separated science curricula and to predict science achievement (PVs BSSSCI01–BSSSCI05). For the curriculum-effect comparison, propensity score matching (propensity scores estimated via stacked ensemble learning; matching via KNN) showed that the integrated curriculum group had significantly higher science achievement than the separated group for each PV, but with small effects (Cohen’s d around 0.20–0.24). For prediction, Random Forest achieved the best performance, with testing R² ≈ 0.51 and testing RMSE ≈ 74.92, outperforming linear regression (R²≈0.21), lasso (≈0.22), decision trees (≈0.29), and neural networks (≈0.22). Feature importance indicated socioeconomic background as the strongest predictor, followed by science confidence and instructional time/experiment frequency. The manuscript uses SHAP for interaction interpretation (predictive explanation, not causal proof) and does not report replicate-weight variance estimation; hierarchical sampling structure is not explicitly modeled beyond using teacher weights for teacher-reported covariates.",
    "research_design_type": "predictive",
